value.value: The quantification of a simple organic or inorganic chemical within a biological specimen. This does not include complex proteins or enzymes.
A quantitative measurement of the amount of potassium present in a sample.
A quantitative measurement of the amount of ketones present in a sample.
A quantitative measurement of the amount of lactate dehydrogenase present in a sample.
A quantitative measurement of the amount of leukocyte esterase present in a sample.
A quantitative measurement of the amount of phosphate present in a sample.
A quantitative measurement of the amount of total protein present in a sample.
The skin of the hinge joint that is located between the thigh and lower leg.

A rare non-encapsulated and poorly circumscribed tumor that usually arises from the posterior neck. It is seen more frequently in men and is characterized by the presence of thick collagen fibers. It may recur but does not metastasize.

A type of diffusion-weighted magnetic resonance imaging (DW-MRI) that maps the diffusion of water in three dimensions, the principal purpose of which is to image the white matter of the brain, specifically measuring the anisotropy, location, and orientation of the neural tracts, which can demonstrate microstructural changes or differences with neuropathology and treatment.
A procedure in which tissue is broken up into small fragments by ultrasound and then removed by aspiration.

An endoscopic technique that allows deep intubation of the small intestine while using a standard endoscope. An inflatable balloon attached to the endoscope's tip acts as a stabilizer and a second balloon that is advanced ahead of the endoscope acts as a pulling device.
A tablet that is suspended in liquid prior to administration to the rectum.
A tablet covered with a layer of gelatin.
A tablet covered with a semipermeable film.
A capsule intended for administration between the cheek and gum of the oral cavity. The active and/or inert ingredient(s) are usually absorbed through the oral mucosa.
A capsule designed to be bitten to release the active and/or inert ingredient(s).
A capsule designed to be chewed to release the active and/or inert ingredient(s).
A capsule covered with a semipermeable film.
A solid composed of dry powdered active and/or inert ingredient(s) covered by an edible shell. The shell consists of two concave pieces of wafer made of flour and water.
A capsule composed of powders intended for oral inhalation. This dose form may also refer to capsules that are intended for use in inhalers.

A benign well-circumscribed lesion arising from the soft tissues. It is characterized by the presence of fibroblasts, lymphoplasmacytic infiltrates, collagenous stroma formation, psammoma bodies, and dystrophic calcifications.
A solid or semi-solid with a sweet taste and intended for oral administration.
A solid or semi-solid in the shape of a three dimensional square.
A solid composed of sucrose, lactose, or other polysaccharides formed into small globular pellets of uniform size which can be classified as homeopathic.
A powder intended to be dusted over the outer surface of the body.
A powder composed of active and/or inert ingredient(s), and a mixture of acids and sodium bicarbonate, which release carbon dioxide when dissolved in water.
A powder that is suspended in liquid prior to administration to the rectum.
A suppository intended for administration to adults.
A suppository intended for administration to children.
A solution or suspension present in a small volume or mass, intended for administration to the rectum.

An insidious poorly circumscribed neoplasm arising from the soft tissues outside the abdomen. It is characterized by the presence of elongated spindle-shaped fibroblasts, vascular collagenous stroma formation, and an infiltrative growth pattern.
A form of treatment derived from Complimentary and Alternative Medicine (CAM) that uses various methods of movement in an effort to enhance physical, mental, and emotional health.
An aerated solution or suspension.
A solution or suspension that produces dense bubbles when combined with water.
